In a bid to stimulate the economy, the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has slashed the interest rate payable on monies deposited in savings accounts from the previous benchmark of around 3.75 per annum to around 1.25% per annum According to a circular issued to all banks, the rate cut is effective from today September 1, 2020. Analysts say the move will allow smaller banks to grow faster and also make it easier for banks to cut lending rates to borrowers. Source By Fabian Ekeruche Lagos -   Alhaji Aminu Gwadabe, a financial expert, has urged the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) to further mop up excess Naira in circulation to sustain its stability. The advice came ahead of the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) meeting of the bank scheduled for July 24… July 21, 2017 In "Top Stories" The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) said it is currently reviewing the extant Guide to Bank Charge which came into effect on April 1, 2013. The review which is in line of periodically enduring that the provisions of the guide accord with the current realities, also seeks to address complaints… March 14, 2016 In "News" Lagos  -  Some financial experts, on Tuesday said the cut in the Monetary Policy Rate (MPR) to 11 per cent if properly harnessed would boost activities at the Nigerian capital market. They told the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in separate interviews in Lagos that the slash would enhance market… November 24, 2015 In "Business"